    <h1>Introduction to Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>
    <p>
        <strong>Object-Oriented Programming</strong> is a programming paradigm based on the concept of <strong>objects</strong>, which represent real-world entities. Objects contain <strong>data</strong> (properties) and <strong>behavior</strong> (methods).
    </p>

    <h2>Key Concepts of OOP</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Classes:</strong> Blueprints for creating objects.</li>
        <li><strong>Objects:</strong> Instances of classes that hold data and behavior.</li>
        <li><strong>Constructors:</strong> Methods to initialize objects.</li>
        <li><strong>Encapsulation:</strong> Restricting access to internal data and providing controlled access.</li>
        <li><strong>Inheritance:</strong> Creating new classes based on existing ones to reuse code.</li>
        <li><strong>Polymorphism:</strong> Allowing objects to take many forms (method overloading/overriding).</li>
        <li><strong>Abstraction:</strong> Hiding complex implementation details and exposing only essential features.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Each concept will be explained in detail in the following subchapters. Things will become much clearer if you go through all the sections in order.</p>

    <h2>Example: Simple OOP in C#</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Creating a Class and Object</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Student
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }

    public void Study()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{Name} is studying.");
    }
}

Student student1 = new Student();
student1.Name = "Alice";
student1.Age = 20;
student1.Study();
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>
        In this example, we created a class <strong>Student</strong> with properties <strong>Name</strong> and <strong>Age</strong> and a method <strong>Study()</strong>.  
        We then created an object of the class and called its method. Everything in this example will be explained in the upcoming subchapters.
    </p>

